properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Walkerville, Walkerville North, Walkerville South.

  • Due to a whale carcass, there could be an increase in shark activity at Walkerville North Beach. 
  • A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
  • While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area.
  • The Victorian Fisheries Authority is assisting Park Rangers with the management of the whale carcass.
  • This Advice message replaces the Advice issued on 22 December.
Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.
What you should do:
  • If you see sharks, report the sighting by calling Triple Zero (000) or notify lifesavers immediately if you are at a patrolled beach.
  • Take extra caution in the area by swimming at patrolled beaches and not surfing or diving in the area.

Staying safe at nearby beaches:
  • Always swim, dive or surf with a friend.
  • Swim between the red and yellow flags on patrolled beaches.
  • Don't swim in places where human or animal waste enters the water.
  • Keep away from large schools of fish, seals or other wildlife as these can attract sharks.
This message was issued by Victorian Fisheries Authority.

The next update is expected by 05/01/2022 06:00 pm or as the situation changes.

For more information on staying safe around sharks:
  • www.vfa.vic.gov.au/shark-smart.
Stay informed:
  • Via www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Call the VicEmergency Hotline to talk to someone about this warning on 1800 226 226 (freecall).
  • People who are deaf, hard of hearing, or who have a speech/communication impairment can contact VicEmergency Hotline via the National Relay Service on 1800 555 677.
  • For help with English, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to telephone VicEmergency Hotline. If you know someone who cannot speak English, provide them with this number.
  • Download the VicEmergency app or follow VicEmergency on Twitter or Facebook.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.action: Walk Two or More Streets Back
properties.location: Nar Nar Goon, Nar Nar Goon North, Pakenham
properties.webBody:
This Watch and Act message is being issued for Nar Nar Goon, Nar Nar Goon North, Pakenham.

  • There is a grassfire at Ryan Rd, Pakenham that is not yet under control.
  • This grassfire is travelling from Ryan Road in a northerly direction towards the Princes Hwy.
  • Firefighters are on scene attacking the fire
  • Firefighting aircraft have been requested to attend
  • Smoke may impact the Princes Hwy
  • This Watch and Act message replaces the Advice issued at 2.27pm. 
If you live directly next to grassland, you may need to move two or more streets away from the fire. Grassfires are unlikely to spread past the first row of houses. 

What you should do: 

Monitor conditions.

If you live right next to grassland, move two streets away:  
  • When you leave remember to take your pets, medications, mobile phone and charger. 
  • If you are away from home, do not return. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends that are away from the warning area.  

If you live two or more streets away from the grassland you should shelter indoors: 
  • Bring your pets indoors. 
  • Close all exterior doors, windows and vents. 
  • Turn off cooling systems. 
  • Monitor conditions. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • Grassfires can start and spread quickly and are extremely dangerous.
  • Roads may be closed in the area to allow for firefighters to attend the fire.
This message was issued by Fire Rescue Victoria.

The next update is expected by 02/01/2022 05:10 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Advice message has been issued for Jarosite Headland, near Bells Beach.

  • Landslip and rockfall has occurred in the Jarosite Headland area.
Stay informed. Stay away from the area. The cliff may continue to move for hours or days afterwards.
What you should do:
  • Landslips and rockfalls are unpredictable and can occur without warning.
  • While the rest of the beach is open, visitors should take note of signage and advice from Parks Victoria staff in the area.
Impacts in your area:
  • A section of beach at Jarosite Headlands, between Point Addis and Southside, has been closed. 
This message was issued by Parks Victoria.

The next update is expected by 05/01/2022 02:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.

This Advice message is being issued for Hattah, Murray-sunset, Ouyen.

  • There is a bushfire 3 kilometres South of Hattah that is contained.
  • The bushfire is along the Calder Highway and in the Hattah-Kulkyne National Park. 
There is currently no threat to communities, but you should continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Monitor weather conditions and warnings. 
  • Review your fire survival plan. 
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes.
Impacts in your area: 

  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads, including the Calder Highway. 
  • The Calder Highway has reopened with new speed restrictions.
  • Emergency services will remain in the area.
  • Emergency services are using bulldozers & aircraft in the area.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
The Threat is Reduced following the grassfire at Langkoop, Poolaijelo, Powers Creek. 

  • This Advice message replaces the Watch and Act issued at 1.03pm on 2 January 2022. 
  • The fire is still burning within areas of private Plantation near Ryans Road. Fire spread has been stopped with crews continuing to build containment lines around the eastern sides of the fire.
  • Surrounding communities may see smoke from fire activity but the threat to private property has reduced. 
People located within Langkoop, Poolaijelo, Powers Creek should stay informed and monitor conditions.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Emergency services will remain in the area, smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads.  
The following roads are closed: 
  •  Casterton-Apsley Road between Dergholm-Edenhope Road and Edenhope-Penola Road. 
  •  Fergusons Road, west of Powers Creek. 
Roadside tree risks 
Firefighters are continuing to assess hazardous trees along roadsides. A number of large gum trees continuing to burn, local Residents should remain cautious of hazardous trees in the area. 

Stock and livestock 
Agriculture Victoria is available to support fire-affected farmers with animal welfare issues. If you have any animal welfare concerns or livestock that need to be assessed, please call Agriculture Victoria District Veterinary Officer Amy Sluggett on 0457 837 840. 

Rainwater tanks  
If you live in a bushfire affected area you should be aware that your rain water tanks could become contaminated from debris and ash or dead animals being flushed into your rainwater tank when it rains, or during fire protecting activity. Untreated water from these sources should not be used for drinking in any event.   
Residents should contact West Wimmera Shire Council to request an Essential Water Replacement form or click on this link Essential Water Replacement form

Asbestos  
Bushfire damage to a building may affect the integrity of building materials and threaten your health. The presence of asbestos in damaged or destroyed properties is a concern. It can risk your health if the asbestos contaminated ash or debris is disturbed and you inhale it. More information is available at the heath.gov.au.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.  

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Watch and Act message is being issued for Kotupna, Lower Moira, Yambuna.

  • There is a bushfire at Yambuna near the Goulburn River that is not yet under control.
Staying close to a building where you can shelter is the safest option, as conditions can change suddenly.

Continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do:
  • Anyone in the bushland should monitor changes, including increased wind speed, change in wind direction, smoke or poor visibility that indicates the situation is changing. 
  • If you are away from home, do not return.

If the situation changes you will need to leave quickly. Plan to:
  • Take your pets, medications, mobile phone and charger.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends that are away from the warning area.
  • Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay.

If you cannot get indoors, last resort options include: 
  • Shelter in the middle of a large open area like a ploughed paddock, football oval or sporting reserve. 
  • Get into a large body of water like a dam, lake, river, the ocean or inground pool. 
  • Try to protect yourself from the fire's heat. 
Impacts in your area:
  • Firefighters are on scene responding to this fire.
  • You will see smoke in the area.
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

The next update is expected by 02/01/2022 06:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

This Advice message is being issued for Cavendish, Gatum, Mooralla.

  • There is a grassfire at Mooralla that is under control.
  • This grassfire is located between East West Road, Luhrs Road, and Cavendish-Glendinning Road. The fire has crossed Luhrs Road. 
  • The fire is approximately 180ha in size. 
  • This Advice message replaces the Advice issued at 4.48pm on Saturday the 1st of January. 
There is currently no threat to you, but you should stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Please drive slowly and carefully in the area, following road signage that will be in place while fire crews work to make the area safe.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Firefighters are attending to this fire. 
  • Smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads.

    The following roads remain closed:
  • Cavendish-Glendinning Road from East-West Road to the corner of the Natimuk-Hamilton Road near Cavendish
  • Luhrs Road from Montana Road to Cavendish-Glendinning Road
The following roads will reopen by 6pm on 1st January:
  • East-West Road from Cavendish-Glendinning Road to Craigs Road, near Mooralla 
  • Montana Road
  • Kelsall Soldier Settlement Road
This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

The next update is expected by 02/01/2022 05:20 pm or as the situation changes.

  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
